This post concerns network centrality measures from ORBIS transport network:

Scheidel, W. and Meeks, E. (May 2, 2012). ORBIS: The Stanford Geospatial Network Model of the Roman World. Retrieved 14 Sep, 2021, from http://orbis.stanford.edu.

With the HANSON Catalogue:

Hanson, J.W. (2016). Cities Database (OXREP databases). Version 1.0. Accessed (2-11-2021): http://oxrep.classics.ox.ac.uk/databases/cities/. DOI: https://doi.org/10.5287/bodleian:eqapevAn8

And the BARRINGTON Atlas:

Backbone of Hanson database adopting its periodization and classification of settlements.

Graph representation

The graph representation is a complement to a cartographical map where some links are easier to see. A graph representation of the ORBIS transport network recorded in orbisnetLbs with coordinates in orbisdcds is from a force directed layout among the nodes, which reflects a sort of centrality measure in terms of repulsion and attraction forces of nodes.

# define scope
scp <- list(ecol=8, pos=0, vcol="white", vcol0=8, fsize=5, cex=.5, rot=180)
# plot valued multigraph with recorded coordinates
multigraph::multigraph(orbisnetLbs, coord=orbisdcds, directed=FALSE, valued=TRUE, scope=scp)

ORBIS transport network

It might be useful to contrast the force directed layout of the graph with the placement of prominent nodes in terms of a given centrality measure.

Settlement names

Obtain settlement labels and look at the head and tail.

# settlement names with crossing-edges
lbs <- dimnames(orbisnetLbs)[[1]]
[1] "Abodiacum"     "Ad fl. Tigrim" "Ad Publicanos" "Ad Tricesimum" "Ad Aras"       "Adramyttium"  
[1] "Skyllaion Pr." "Siphnos"       "Syros"         "Telos"         "Tenos"         "Thera"

Centrality measures based on neighbours

The ORBIS transport network data is dichotomized to compute the centrality measures. This is since what is important is solely the existence of connections among settlements, and transportation costs is for extensions to the resulted centrality scores.

# use the minimum non-zero value and above for links
orbisnetd <- multiplex::dichot(orbisnetLbs, c=min(orbisnetLbs[orbisnetLbs>0]))

Degree centrality

Degree centrality measures a nodes importance based on the number of neighbours.

Compute degree centrality by column sum in the adjacency matrix orbisdnet. Since the ORBIS transport network is undirected, in-degree and out-degree centralities are indistinguishable, and row sum leads to the same result.

# outdegree centrality from column sums
onetdc <- colSums(orbisnetd)

And look at prominent nodes in the graph representing the Roman Empire transportation network.

# top six nodes degree centrality
require("magrittr")
onetdc %>% 
  sort(decreasing=TRUE) %>% 
  head(10)
            Delos            Rhodos          Carthago      Ostia/Portus         Lilybaeum 
               21                20                11                10                10 
             Roma            Paphos    Portus Pachyni           Messana Apollonia-Sozousa 
                9                 9                 9                 9                 9 
# select settlement names for plotting
sel <- head(names(sort(onetdc,decreasing=TRUE)),10)
# node sizes according to degree centrality scores
scp <- list(coord=orbisdcds, ecol=1, directed=FALSE, lbs=lbb, pos=0, vcol="white", vcol0=8, fsize=5, rot=180)
multigraph::multigraph(orbisnetLbs, scope=scp, cex=as.vector(onetdc), sel=sel, bg=8)

Degree centrality (top 10)

Eigenvector centrality

Another centrality measure based on neighbours is eigenvector centrality, which measures a nodes importance while considering the number and importance of its neighbours.

To compute eigenvector centrality, use "igraph" R package

  • https://CRAN.R-project.org/package=igraph.
require("magrittr")
onetec <- orbisnetd %>% 
  igraph::graph.adjacency() %>% 
  igraph::eigen_centrality() %>% 
  use_series("vector") %>% 
  as.vector(mode="list") %>% 
  unlist()

Prominent nodes in terms of eigenvector centrality.

# top ten nodes eigenvector centrality
require("magrittr")
onetec %>% 
  sort(decreasing=TRUE) %>% 
  head(10)
     Rhodos       Delos       Samos         Kos     Ephesus      Myndos  Astypaleia     Amorgos 
  1.0000000   0.9525685   0.5881245   0.5831718   0.5138541   0.4343745   0.4143912   0.4140000 
Sounion Pr.    Selinous 
  0.3968902   0.3706105 
# select settlement names for plotting
sel <- head(names(sort(onetec,decreasing=TRUE)),10)
# scale-up node sizes for better visibility
scp <- list(directed=FALSE, pos=0, ecol="white", vcol="white", vcol0=8, fsize=5, rot=180, bg=8)
multigraph::multigraph(orbisnetLbs, coord=orbisdcds, scope=scp, lbs=lbb, cex=as.vector(onetec)*5L, sel=sel)

Eigenvector centrality (top 10)

Settlements

The two most central settlements in terms of degree and eigenvector centrality are ports in the Aegean Sea.

DELOS

(Greek )

Achaia, port in archipelago Cyclades, Aegean Sea.

Between 900 BC and 100 AD (or around the 8th century AD (Dodd, 2020)).

Birthplace of Apollo and Artemis.

Sacred Harbour and Sanctuary of Zeus in Mount Kynthos as one of three conical mounds.

Proximal to Pergamum that was the leading city of Roman province of Asia, in the coast of Asia Minor, and a major pilgrim centre for the Greek god of medicine Asclepius.

According to Hanson catalogue, Delos is geographically adjacent to Paros and Naxus.

RHODOS

(Greek , Rhodus in Hanson)

Asia, largest of the Dodecanese islands, Aegean Sea.

From 408 BC

Colossus of Rhodes, a massive statue of the Greek god of the sun Helios, and The Acropolis with the Temple of Apollo.

Strong commercial ties and alliance with the Ptolemies in Egypt.

According to Hanson catalogue, Rhodos is geographically adjacent to Lindus, Cnidus, Caunus, Lydai?, and Castabus.

CARTHAGO

(Phoenician for new town)

Africa Proconsularis, port in the north coast of African continent.

By tradition, founded by the Phoenicians 814 BC.

Important trade centre in the western Mediterranean Sea.

SAMOS

(Greek )

Asia, island in the eastern of the Aegean Sea.

From 6th century BC

School of sculptors, architects, and manufacture of pottery.

Centrality measures based on shortest path

Besides neighbours, centrality measures on networks are also based on geodesic or shortest path, which applies on a binary network.

Betweenness centrality

Betweenness centrality measures the fraction of shortest paths between all other nodes that run through the node.

# compute betweenness centrality
require("magrittr")
onetbc <- orbisnetd %>% 
  igraph::graph.adjacency() %>% 
  igraph::betweenness() %>% 
  as.vector(mode="list") %>% 
  unlist()

Then look at prominent nodes in terms of betweenness centrality.

# top ten nodes betweenness centrality
require("magrittr")
onetbc %>% 
  sort(decreasing=TRUE) %>% 
  head(10)
           Messana         Alexandria             Rhodos              Gades  Apollonia-Sozousa 
         204303.79          184557.32          133234.20          108498.27           73140.05 
           Olisipo    Sallentinum Pr. Flavium Brigantium   Acroceraunia Pr.          Lilybaeum 
          69337.27           64974.03           63538.38           61357.27           58087.15

What is remarkable with betweenness centrality and the other measures based on shortest path is that the most prominent settlements are all ports within the Roman World and constitute strategic communication points having both maritime and terrestrial routes from which many other nodes depend on them for transportation purposes.

Centrality measures based on shortest path highlights nodes top centrality scores in the graph representations.

# select settlement names for plotting
sel <- head(names(sort(onetbc,decreasing=TRUE)),10)
# new labels with selected nodes
lbb <- rep("",length(onetbc)); vec <- vector()
for(i in seq_len(length(sel))) vec <- append(vec, which(lbs%in%sel[i]))
lbb[vec] <- sel
# clustering for node colors
ccl <- vector(length=length(lbb)); ccl[which(lbb=="")] <- 1L
scp <- list(directed=FALSE, pos=0, ecol=1, vcol0="white", vcol=c("white",8), clu=ccl, fsize=5, rot=180, bg=8)
# node sizes with centrality scores
multigraph::multigraph(orbisnetLbs, coord=orbisdcds, scope=scp, cex=as.vector(onetbc), sel=sel)

Betweenness centrality (top 10)

Closeness centrality

Closeness centrality is the reciprocal of average shortest path distance.

(Eccentricity centrality takes the maximum geodesic path distance)

# compute closeness centrality
require("magrittr")
onetcc <- orbisnetd %>% 
  igraph::graph.adjacency() %>% 
  igraph::closeness() %>% 
  as.vector(mode="list") %>% 
  unlist()

Then look at high score nodes in terms of closeness centrality.

# 10 nodes with highest closeness scores
require("magrittr")
onetcc %>% 
  sort(decreasing=TRUE) %>% 
  head(10) %>% 
  unlist()
          Messana        Alexandria             Gades Apollonia-Sozousa         Lilybaeum 
     0.0002347418      0.0002275313      0.0002237136      0.0002176752      0.0002171081 
           Rhodos    Portus Pachyni       Ichthys Pr.           Caralis            Regium 
     0.0002145923      0.0002118195      0.0002103492      0.0002103049      0.0002101282

As with betweenness centrality that is also based on shortest path distance, the most prominent settlements in terms of closeness centrality are all ports within the Roman World. However, the values tend to span a rather small dynamic range from smallest to largest, which means that interpretation is not straightforward.

# select settlement names for plotting
sel <- head(names(sort(onetcc,decreasing=TRUE)),10)
# new labels with selected nodes
lbb <- rep("",length(onetcc)); vec <- vector()
for(i in seq_len(length(sel))) vec <- append(vec, which(lbs%in%sel[i]))
lbb[vec] <- sel
# clustering for node colors
ccl <- vector(length=length(lbb)); ccl[which(lbb=="")] <- 1L
scp <- list(directed=FALSE, pos=0, ecol=1, vcol0="white", vcol=c("white",8), clu=ccl, fsize=5, rot=180, bg=8)
# scale-up node sizes for better visibility
multigraph::multigraph(orbisnetLbs, coord=orbisdcds, scope=scp, cex=as.vector(onetcc)*8000L, sel=sel)

Closeness centrality (top 10)

Settlements

The two most central settlements in terms of betweenness and closeness centrality are ports in the Aegean Sea.

MESSANA

(Sicilian MISSINA, from ancient Greek city )

Sicily, port in the Mediterranean, between Tyrrhenian Sea and Ionian Sea.

Proximal to Italian peninsula (5 km).

From 730 BC.

With a pharos, base for Roman military activity.

According to Hanson catalogue, Messana is geographically adjacent to Regium, Mylae, and by sea with Locri and Vibo Valentia in the Italian peninsula.

ALEXANDRIA

(Greek not to be confused with Alexandria Troas in Asia Minor)

Aegyptus, port in the African continent.

From Ptolemaic dynasty

One of the largest city in the ancient world connecting the Mediterranean Sea and the Red Sea ruled by a complex Greek bureaucracy.

Intellectual and cultural centre (later on flocked to Rome)

According to Hanson catalogue, Alexandria is geographically adjacent to Metelis and Tebtunis.

GADES

(Urba Iulia Gaditana)

Baetica, port in the Iberian peninsula

Established between 8th and 10th century BC.

Old Carthaginian colony disputed with the Phoenicians.

Strategic point to control of the western Mediterranean Sea.

Valued networks

For a valued or weighted version of this network, we create a valued edge list in orbisv with send, receive, and tie weights.

orbisv <- orbise[,c(1,2,5)]
tail(orbisv)
     source target expense
2203  50800  50779   0.059
2204  50800  50783   0.056
2205  50801  50573   0.109
2206  50801  50582   0.074
2207  50801  50777   0.033
2208  50801  50785   0.034

Centrality measures in valued networks

Different centrality measures for weighted networks are found in "tnet" package where argument alpha is a tuning parameter that serves to combine nodes degree and edges strength. An alpha value of zero ignores edges weights; i.e. binarize the network, while an alpha value of one disregards nodes number of incident edges.

The following examples are for three centrality measures spliting equally node degree and edge strength in the weighted system.

# degree centrality valued
tail(tnet::degree_w(net=orbisv, measure=c("degree","output","alpha"), alpha=0.5))
          node degree output     alpha
[50796,] 50796      3  1.270 1.9519221
[50797,] 50797      2  0.080 0.4000000
[50798,] 50798      2  0.061 0.3492850
[50799,] 50799      2  0.095 0.4358899
[50800,] 50800      4  0.165 0.8124038
[50801,] 50801      4  0.250 1.0000000
# betweenness centrality valued 
tail(tnet::betweenness_w(net=orbisv, alpha=0.5))
          node betweenness
[50796,] 50796        1352
[50797,] 50797           0
[50798,] 50798           0
[50799,] 50799           0
[50800,] 50800           0
[50801,] 50801         120
# closeness centrality valued 
tail(tnet::closeness_w(net=orbisv, alpha=0.5)) 
        node    closeness  n.closeness
[673,] 50796 1.298232e-04 1.917624e-07
[674,] 50797 9.325457e-05 1.377468e-07
[675,] 50798 7.390118e-05 1.091598e-07
[676,] 50799 1.105484e-04 1.632915e-07
[677,] 50800 7.850528e-05 1.159605e-07
[678,] 50801 9.979916e-05 1.474138e-07

Eigenvector centrality in valued networks

There is no support in "tnet" package to compute eigenvector centrality scores for valued networks. With an unclear documentation, "igraph" package has a weights argument in eigen_centrality() function to run eigenvector centrality for weighted networks. Since "tnet" requires "igraph", however, the implementation of eigenvector centrality for valued networks is not straightforward.
